<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:department>Experimental Psychology</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/46660362-46DC-4508-8D05-A6D846A44E12"><gtr:id>46660362-46DC-4508-8D05-A6D846A44E12</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>INCI</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>AYHAN</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI02302X%2F1"><gtr:id>B3AEC92D-35F1-4065-BACF-8B8816969C6C</gtr:id><gtr:title>An fMRI investigation of visual time perception</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I02302X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The apparent duration of brief intervals can be manipulated in a small region of the visual field by visual flicker adaptation (Johnston et al, Cun-ent Biology, 2006). The variable response of neurons as a function of flicker frequency is referred to as their temporal tuning. Adaptation-based time compression has recently been linked to changes in the temporal tuning of the magnocellular (MC) neurons (Ayhan, et al, Joumal of Vision, 2009). Also some dyslexics, unlike controls, show an apparent temporal expansion after adaptation to slow motion (Johnston et al. Vision Research, 2008).&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Dyslexia is a condition characterised by reading and spelling difficulties. It has been proposed that some dyslexics may suffer from a deficit in MC processing. Our aim is to investigate the MC hypothesis tiy exploring the relationship between the neural activity (measured using fMRI) of normal and dyslexic subjects to flickering stimuli and changes in perceived duration measured psychophysically. Differences between nonnals and dyslexics in lateral geniculate nucleus activation or adaptation would point to a functional difference in earty visual processing. Correlated changes in temporal tuning and temporal compression induced by flicker adaptation would provide further evidence for the involvement of the MC pathway in time perception.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>92379</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/I02302X/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352-1AB0B6DC5F23</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Psychology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530-BA5E-562216587E68</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:per